RCV_{C}^{'}\left(t\right)+V_{C}\left(t\right) & = & V\left(t\right)\nonumber \\
V_{C}^{'}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{RC}V_{C}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{1}{RC}V\left(t\right)\label{eq:rccircuit}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Solving this first order ODE is easy.
 The solution is the sum of the solution to the homogeneous ODE
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{C}^{'}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{RC}V_{C}\left(t\right) & = & 0\\
 & \Rightarrow\\
V_{C}\left(t\right) & = & V_{C}\left(0\right)e^{-\frac{t}{RC}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

plus the particular solution, using integrating factors: if you multiply
 both sides of eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rccircuit"

\end_inset

 by a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\left(t\right)V_{C}^{'}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{RC}\mu\left(t\right)V_{C}\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{RC}\mu\left(t\right)V\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(\mu\left(t\right)V_{C}\left(t\right)\right) & = & \mu\left(t\right)V_{C}^{'}\left(t\right)+\mu^{'}\left(t\right)V_{C}\left(t\right)\label{eq:intgfac}\\
 & = & \mu\left(t\right)V_{C}^{'}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{RC}\mu\left(t\right)V_{C}\left(t\right)\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\left(\mu\left(t\right)V_{C}\left(t\right)\right)=\frac{1}{RC}\mu\left(t\right)V\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

and you can just integrate both sides.
 Eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:intgfac"

\end_inset

 holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{'}\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{RC}\mu\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 which necessitates that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(t\right)=e^{t/RC}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\left(e^{t/RC}V_{C}\left(t\right)\right)=\frac{1}{RC}e^{t/RC}V\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
e^{t/RC}V_{C}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{1}{RC}\int e^{t/RC}V\left(t\right)dt\\
 & \Rightarrow\\
V_{C}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{e^{-t/RC}}{RC}\int e^{t/RC}V\left(t\right)dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Finally if 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(t\right)=e^{j\omega t}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{C}\left(t\right) & = & e^{-t/RC}V_{C}\left(0\right)+\frac{e^{-t/RC}}{RC}\int e^{t/RC}e^{j\omega t}dt\\
 & = & e^{-t/RC}V_{C}\left(0\right)+\frac{e^{j\omega t}}{1+RCj\omega}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(0\right)=0$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{C}\left(t\right) & = & \frac{1}{1+RCj\omega}e^{j\omega t}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{1+RCj\omega}V\left(t\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus the frequency response 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H\left(j\omega\right)=\frac{1}{1+RCj\omega}
\]

\end_inset

If one plots the amplitude of the frequency response versus frequency it's
 a mountain around 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=0$
\end_inset

 and slopes down steadily as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\omega\right|$
\end_inset

 increases.
 So it scales down high frequencies.
 There are trade-offs though.
 The impulse response of this system is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{RC}e^{-t/RC}u\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

and the step response is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(t\right)=\left(1-e^{-t/RC}\right)u\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

For the filter to functio as expected 
\begin_inset Formula $RC$
\end_inset

 should be high.
 But then the step response takes a very long time to reach its steady state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the voltage drop across the resistor in the RC circuit function
 as a high-pass filter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Discrete-time filters from Difference equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Discrete-time filters correspond to difference equations, just like how
 continuous-time filters correspond to ODEs.
 Nevermind implementation
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
FPGAs?
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 There are several types of LTI systems described by difference equations:
 recursive difference equations are considered infinite impulse response
 (IIR) systems because the ouput is dependent on the entire past of the
 input, non-recursive difference equations are considered finite impulse
 response (FIR) systems because the output is dependent on only the finite
 past of the input.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general form of an FIR nonrecursive difference equation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\left[n\right]=\sum_{k=-N}^{M}b_{k}x\left[n-k\right]
\]

\end_inset

This resembles a moving average: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(M+N+1\right)$
\end_inset

 contiguous values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

 are weighted by 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 and summed; for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}$
\end_inset

 it's the 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 values preceding 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 values proceeding 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Take for example 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\left[n\right]=\frac{1}{3}\left(x\left[n-1\right]+x\left[n\right]+x\left[n+1\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

The impulse response of this system is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\left[n\right]=\frac{1}{3}\left(\delta\left[n+1\right]+\delta\left[n\right]+\delta\left[n-1\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

Why? By the properties of impulse response and convolution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
y\left[n\right] & = & x\left[n\right]\star h\left[n\right]\\
 & = & \sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left[k\right]h\left[n-k\right]\\
 & = & \frac{1}{3}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left[k\right]\left(\delta\left[n-\left(k+1\right)\right]+\delta\left[n-\left(k\right)\right]+\delta\left[n-\left(k-1\right)\right]\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{3}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left[k\right]\left(\delta\left[\left(n-1\right)-k\right]+\delta\left[n-k\right]+\delta\left[\left(n+1\right)-k\right]\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{3}\left(x\left[n-1\right]+x\left[n\right]+x\left[n+1\right]\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H\left(e^{j\omega}\right) & = & \sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}h\left[k\right]e^{-jk\omega}\\
 &  & \frac{1}{3}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}\left(\delta\left[k+1\right]+\delta\left[k\right]+\delta\left[k-1\right]\right)e^{-jk\omega}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{3}\left(e^{j\omega}+1+e^{-j\omega}\right)=\frac{1}{3}\left(1+2\cos\left(\omega\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which when plotted looks like a low-pass filter but it does not have a sharp
 transition from passband to stopband, and without parameters to tweak there's
 nothing that can be done.
 Alternatively
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
y\left[n\right] & = & \frac{1}{N+M+1}\sum_{k=-N}^{M}x\left[n-k\right]\\
 & \Rightarrow\\
h\left[n\right] & = & \frac{1}{N+M+1}\sum_{k=-N}^{M}\delta\left[n+k\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H\left(e^{j\omega}\right) & = & \frac{1}{N+M+1}\sum_{k=-N}^{M}e^{-j\omega k}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{N+M+1}e^{j\omega\left(\frac{N-M}{2}\right)}\frac{\sin\left(\frac{N+M+1}{2}\omega\right)}{\sin\left(\omega/2\right)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which has a much sharper transition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fourier Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fourier series only exist for periodic signals (discrete-time or continuous-time
).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fourier transform for aperiodic signals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the periodic square wave with width 
\begin_inset Formula $2T_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\left(t\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \left|t\right|<T_{1}\\
0 & T_{1}<\left|t\right|<T
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The Fourier series coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=\frac{2\sin\left(k\omega_{0}T_{1}\right)}{k\omega_{0}T}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=2\pi/T$
\end_inset

.
 An alternative perspective on these coefficients is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ta_{k}=\left.\frac{2\sin\left(\omega T_{1}\right)}{\omega}\right|_{\omega=k\omega_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

I.e.
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $Ta_{k}$
\end_inset

 are equally spaced samples of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $2\sin\left(\omega T_{1}\right)/\omega$
\end_inset

 at multiples of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $T\rightarrow\infty,\omega_{0}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and the envelope function is sampled more finely, and the scaled Fourier
 coefficients 
\emph on
become
\emph default
 the function.
 What else happens as a 
\begin_inset Formula $T\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

? The square-wave becomes aperiodic
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The periodic repetitions move off to infinity.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This is the general methodology for studying aperiodic signals: approximate
 them by a sequence of periodic signals with ever increasing period.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{T}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 be the periodic approximation to the aperiodic signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The FS representation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{x}_{T}\left(t\right)=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}a_{k}e^{jk\omega_{0}t}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=\frac{1}{T}\int_{-T/2}^{T/2}\tilde{x}_{T}\left(t\right)e^{-jk\omega_{0}t}dt
\]

\end_inset

Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{T}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 agree on 
\begin_inset Formula $-T/2<t<T/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)=0$
\end_inset

 otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=\frac{1}{T}\int_{-T/2}^{T/2}x_{T}\left(t\right)e^{-jk\omega_{0}t}dt=\frac{1}{T}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x_{T}\left(t\right)e^{-jk\omega_{0}t}dt
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ta_{k}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x_{T}\left(t\right)e^{-jk\omega_{0}t}dt
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(j\omega\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x_{T}\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt$
\end_inset

 be the envelope function.then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Ta_{k} & = & \left.X\left(j\omega\right)\right|_{\omega=k\omega_{0}}\\
 & \iff\\
a_{k} & = & \frac{1}{T}\left.X\left(j\omega\right)\right|_{\omega=k\omega_{0}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Keep in mind the meaningful quantity is 
\begin_inset Formula $Ta_{k}$
\end_inset

, not just 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $Ta_{k}$
\end_inset

 are equispaced samples from the Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, not 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The synthesis equation for the periodic 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tilde{x}\left(t\right) & = & \sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{1}{T}X\left(jk\omega_{0}\right)e^{jk\omega_{0}t}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}X\left(jk\omega_{0}\right)e^{jk\omega_{0}t}\omega_{0}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $k\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 becomes the continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tilde{x}\left(t\right) & \rightarrow & x\left(t\right)\\
 & \text{and}\\
\tilde{x}\left(t\right) & \rightarrow & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}X\left(j\omega\right)e^{j\omega t}d\omega
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)=e^{-at}u\left(t\right),\;a>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
X\left(j\omega\right) & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{-at}u\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt\\
 & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-\left(a+j\omega\right)t}dt\\
 & = & \left.-\frac{1}{a+j\omega}e^{-\left(a+j\omega\right)t}\right|_{0}^{\infty}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{a+j\omega}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This is of course the frequency response for the lowpass RC filter with
 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1/RC$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This whole process can be inverted: let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 be a finite-duration signal that is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 over exactly one period, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $s\leq t\leq s+T$
\end_inset

.
 Then since generally the Fourier coefficients for the Fourier series representa
tion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 can be computed by integrating over one period
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fouriercoefficients"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a_{k} & = & \frac{1}{T}\int_{s}^{s+T}\tilde{x}\left(t\right)e^{-jk\omega_{0}t}dt\\
 & = & \frac{1}{T}\int_{s}^{s+T}x\left(t\right)e^{-jk\omega_{0}t}dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 out side of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(s,s+T\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a_{k} & = & \frac{1}{T}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(t\right)e^{-jk\omega_{0}t}dt\\
 & = & \frac{1}{T}\left.X\left(j\omega\right)\right|_{\omega=k\omega_{0}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

A very useful fact in practice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fourier transforms for periodic signals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A periodic signal is just a superposition of pure frequencies.
 What kind of signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 has fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(j\omega\right)=2\pi\delta\left(\omega-\omega_{0}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Using the synthesis equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x\left(t\right) & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}2\pi\delta\left(\omega-\omega_{0}\right)e^{j\omega t}d\omega\\
 & = & e^{j\omega_{0}t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore the Fourier transform of any periodic signal which has Fourier
 representation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\left(t\right)=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}a_{k}e^{jk\omega_{0}t}
\]

\end_inset

is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(j\omega\right)=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}2\pi a_{k}\delta\left(\omega-k\omega_{0}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which makes sense since then sampling from this Fourier transform
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a_{k} & = & \frac{1}{T}\left.X\left(j\omega\right)\right|_{\omega=k\omega_{0}}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{T}\sum_{k'=-\infty}^{\infty}2\pi a_{k'}\delta\left(k\omega_{0}-k'\omega_{0}\right)\\
 & \approx & \frac{2\pi}{T}a_{k}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convolution property
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that if a periodic signal has a Fourier series representation then
 the response of an LTI system is again a Fourier series, with coefficients
 multiplied by the frequency response of the system.
 The Fourier transform enables this same sort of analysis for aperiodic
 signals.
 Remeber the interpretation of the Fourier transform as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}X\left(j\omega\right)e^{j\omega t}=\lim_{\omega_{0}\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{2\pi}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}X\left(jk\omega_{0}\right)e^{jk\omega_{0}t}\omega_{0}
\]

\end_inset

Being very sloppy with limits: the response of an LTI system is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
y\left(t\right) & = & \lim_{\omega_{0}\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{2\pi}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}X\left(jk\omega_{0}\right)H\left(jk\omega_{0}\right)e^{jk\omega_{0}t}\omega_{0}\\
 &  & =\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}X\left(j\omega\right)H\left(j\omega\right)e^{j\omega t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}Y\left(j\omega\right)e^{j\omega t}d\omega
\]

\end_inset

it turns out that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y\left(j\omega\right)=X\left(j\omega\right)H\left(j\omega\right)\label{eq:prodfreqspace}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A little more formally: since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\left(t\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(\tau\right)h\left(t-\tau\right)d\tau
\]

\end_inset

it's the case that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Y\left(j\omega\right) & = & \mathfrak{F}\left\{ y\left(t\right)\right\} =\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\left[\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(\tau\right)h\left(t-\tau\right)d\tau\right]e^{-j\omega t}dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Interchanging the order of integration
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Y\left(j\omega\right) & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(\tau\right)\left[\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}h\left(t-\tau\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt\right]d\tau
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

By the time-shifting property of the Fourier transform
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{F}\left\{ x\left(t-t_{0}\right)\right\} =e^{-j\omega t_{0}}\mathfrak{F}\left\{ x\left(t\right)\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Y\left(j\omega\right) & = & H\left(j\omega\right)\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(\tau\right)e^{-j\omega\tau}d\tau\\
 & = & H\left(j\omega\right)X\left(j\omega\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\left(t\right)=h\left(t\right)\star x\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y\left(j\omega\right)=H\left(j\omega\right)X\left(j\omega\right)
\]

\end_inset

This is useful for computing the responses of LTI systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider the RC circuit system with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\left(t\right)=e^{-at}u\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

with input 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\left(t\right)=e^{-bt}u\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Y\left(j\omega\right) & = & \frac{1}{\left(a+j\omega\right)\left(b+j\omega\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{A}{a+j\omega}+\frac{B}{b+j\omega}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{b-a}\left[\frac{1}{a+j\omega}-\frac{1}{b+j\omega}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\left(t\right)=\frac{\left(e^{-at}-e^{-bt}\right)}{b-a}u\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

But if 
\begin_inset Formula $b=a$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Y\left(j\omega\right) & = & \frac{1}{\left(a+j\omega\right)^{2}}\\
 & = & j\frac{d}{d\omega}\left(\frac{1}{a+j\omega}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then the dual differentiation property
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{F}\left\{ x^{'}\left(t\right)\right\} =j\omega X\left(j\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{F}^{-1}\left\{ X'\left(j\omega\right)\right\} =-jtx\left(t\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
y\left(t\right) & = & j\mathfrak{F}^{-1}\left\{ \frac{d}{d\omega}\left(\frac{1}{a+j\omega}\right)\right\} \\
 & = & j\left(-jtx\left(t\right)\right)\\
 & = & te^{-at}u\left(t\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modulation property
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By duality
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{F}\left\{ s\left(t\right)p\left(t\right)\right\} =\frac{1}{2\pi}\left(S\left(j\omega\right)\star P\left(j\omega\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

This will be useful for sampling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Overkill
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the continuous-time LTI system
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{k=0}^{N}a_{k}\frac{d^{k}y\left(t\right)}{dt^{k}}=\sum_{k=0}^{M}b_{k}\frac{d^{k}x\left(t\right)}{dt^{k}}
\]

\end_inset

This is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

th-order ordinary differential equation.
 What's the frequency response of this system? Take the FT of both sides
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathfrak{F}\left\{ \sum_{k=0}^{N}a_{k}\frac{d^{k}y\left(t\right)}{dt^{k}}\right\}  & = & \mathfrak{F}\left\{ \sum_{k=0}^{M}b_{k}\frac{d^{k}x\left(t\right)}{dt^{k}}\right\} 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

By linearity of the FT
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{k=0}^{N}a_{k}\mathfrak{F}\left\{ \frac{d^{k}y\left(t\right)}{dt^{k}}\right\}  & = & \sum_{k=0}^{M}b_{k}\mathfrak{F}\left\{ \frac{d^{k}x\left(t\right)}{dt^{k}}\right\} 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

By the differentiation property of the FT
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{k=0}^{N}a_{k}\left(j\omega\right)^{k}Y\left(j\omega\right) & = & \sum_{k=0}^{M}b_{k}\left(j\omega\right)^{k}X\left(j\omega\right)\\
Y\left(j\omega\right)\sum_{k=0}^{N}a_{k}\left(j\omega\right)^{k} & = & X\left(j\omega\right)\sum_{k=0}^{M}b_{k}\left(j\omega\right)^{k}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore by eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prodfreqspace"

\end_inset

 the frequency response
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H\left(j\omega\right)=\frac{\sum_{k=0}^{M}b_{k}\left(j\omega\right)^{k}}{\sum_{k=0}^{N}a_{k}\left(j\omega\right)^{k}}
\]

\end_inset

Note that the coefficients of this rational polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $j\omega$
\end_inset

 are those of the original differential equation, and so the frequency response
 can be simply read off from the same DE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider the ODE
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}y\left(t\right)}{dt^{2}}+4\frac{dy\left(t\right)}{dt}+3y\left(t\right)=\frac{dx\left(t\right)}{dt}+2x\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

The frequency response is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H\left(j\omega\right) & = & \frac{\left(j\omega\right)+2}{\left(j\omega\right)^{2}+4\left(j\omega\right)+3}\\
 & = & \frac{\left(j\omega\right)+2}{\left(j\omega+1\right)\left(j\omega+3\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{1/2}{j\omega+1}+\frac{1/2}{j\omega+3}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(e^{-t}+e^{-3t}\right)u\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discrete-time Fourier Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just like there exists a Fourier transform for continuous-time aperiodic
 signals which fortifies the Fourier series (which only exists for periodic
 signals) there exists a Discrete-time Fourier transform for discrete-time
 aperiodic signal which fortifies the Discrete-time Fourier series
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Which has the same nice properties as the continuous time Fourier series.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discrete-time Fourier transform aperiodic signals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a general finite-duration sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

 which has support 
\begin_inset Formula $-N_{1}\leq n\leq N_{2}$
\end_inset

 and its periodic analog 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

 with period 
\begin_inset Formula $N>N_{1}+N_{2}+1$
\end_inset

.
 By eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:discfs"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{x}\left[n\right]=\sum_{k=\left\langle N\right\rangle }a_{k}e^{jk\omega_{0}n}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=\left\langle N\right\rangle }\tilde{x}\left[n\right]e^{-jk\omega_{0}n}
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]=\tilde{x}\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

 over a period that includes the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

 is zero outside of its support
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=-N_{1}}^{N_{2}}x\left[n\right]e^{-jk\omega_{0}n}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left[n\right]e^{-jk\omega_{0}n}
\]

\end_inset

Define 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(e^{j\omega}\right)=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left[n\right]e^{-j\omega n}$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=\frac{1}{N}X\left(e^{jk\omega_{0}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=2\pi/N$
\end_inset

 is the spacing the frequency domain.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tilde{x}\left[n\right] & = & \frac{1}{N}\sum_{k=\left\langle N\right\rangle }X\left(e^{jk\omega_{0}}\right)e^{jk\omega_{0}n}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\sum_{k=\left\langle N\right\rangle }X\left(e^{jk\omega_{0}}\right)e^{jk\omega_{0}n}\omega_{0}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}N=2\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 becomes the continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tilde{x}\left[n\right] & \rightarrow & x\left[n\right]\\
 & \text{and}\\
\tilde{x}\left[n\right] & \rightarrow & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{2\pi}X\left(e^{j\omega}\right)e^{j\omega n}d\omega
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discrete-time Fourier transform periodic signals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the continuous case periodic signals can be represented using the
 DTFT.
 Consider the signal 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\left[n\right]=e^{j\omega_{0}n}
\]

\end_inset

The DTFT of this signal is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(e^{j\omega}\right)=\sum_{l=-\infty}^{\infty}2\pi\delta\left(\omega-\omega_{0}-2\pi l\right)
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(e^{j\omega}\right)$
\end_inset

 must be periodic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 with period 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is because complex exponentials are 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 periodic.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Now consider the periodic sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

 with period 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 with Fourier series representation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\left[n\right]=\sum_{k=\left\langle N\right\rangle }a_{k}e^{jk\omega_{0}n}
\]

\end_inset

Then the DTFT is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(e^{j\omega}\right)=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}2\pi a_{k}\delta\left(\omega-\omega_{0}k\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sampling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a signal is band limited - its spectrum is zero outside some finite range
 of frequencies - and if it's sampled, with sampling period 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}$
\end_inset

, at a high enough rate
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Twice the highest frequency component.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 then the signal can be reconstructed faithfully from just the samples.
 This is the Shannon sampling theorem.
 The frequency at which the signal should be sampled is called the Nyquist
 sampling frequency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the impulse-train 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(t\right)=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}\delta\left(t-kT_{s}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Then the sampled signal is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{p}\left(t\right)=x\left(t\right)p\left(t\right)\approxeq\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(kT_{s}\right)\delta\left(t-kT_{s}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\approxeq$
\end_inset

 is because we all know this isn't really true - the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is only defined under the integral.
 But by the multiplcation property of continuous signals
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{p}\left(j\omega\right)\coloneqq\mathcal{F}\left\{ x\left(t\right)p\left(t\right)\right\} =\mathcal{F}\left\{ x_{p}\left(t\right)\right\} =\frac{1}{2\pi}\left(\mathcal{F}\left\{ x\left(t\right)\right\} \star\mathcal{F}\left\{ p\left(t\right)\right\} \right)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\left(X\left(j\omega\right)\star P\left(j\omega\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

Now what is 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(j\omega\right)$
\end_inset

? This is the real sampling mechanism.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}\left(t\right)=\sum_{k=-n}^{n}\delta\left(t-kT_{s}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{n}\left(j\omega\right) & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}p_{k}\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\sum_{k=-n}^{n}\delta\left(t-kT_{s}\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt\\
 & = & \sum_{k=-n}^{n}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\delta\left(t-kT_{s}\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt\\
 & = & \sum_{k=-n}^{n}e^{-j\omega kT_{s}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}\left(j\omega\right)\rightarrow P\left(j\omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{k=-n}^{n}e^{-j\omega kT_{s}} & = & e^{j\omega T_{s}}\left(1+e^{-j\omega T_{s}}+\left(e^{-j\omega T_{s}}\right)^{2}+\cdots+\left(e^{-j\omega T_{s}}\right)^{2n}\right)\\
 & = & e^{j\omega T_{s}}\left(\frac{1-e^{-j\omega\left(2n+1\right)T_{s}}}{1-e^{-j\omega T_{s}}}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{e^{j\omega T_{s}}e^{-j\omega\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)T_{s}}}{e^{-j\omega T_{s}/2}}\left(\frac{e^{j\omega\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)T_{s}}-e^{-j\omega\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)T_{s}}}{e^{j\omega T_{s}/2}-e^{-j\omega T_{s}/2}}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{2j\sin\left(\omega\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)T_{s}\right)}{2j\sin\left(\omega T_{s}/2\right)}=\frac{\sin\left(\omega\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)T_{s}\right)}{\sin\left(\omega T_{s}/2\right)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This is a function that is a series of sinc functions with peaks of magnitude
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2n+1\right)$
\end_inset

 at multiples of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi/T_{s}$
\end_inset

, and as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 it approaches a series of impulses with area equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi/T_{s}$
\end_inset

, since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\pi/T_{s}}^{\pi/T_{s}}\sum_{k=-n}^{n}e^{-j\omega kT_{s}}d\omega=\sum_{k=-n}^{n}\underbrace{\int_{-\pi/T_{s}}^{\pi/T_{s}}e^{-j\omega kT_{s}}d\omega}_{0\text{ unless }k=0}=\int_{-\pi/T_{s}}^{\pi/T_{s}}d\omega=\frac{2\pi}{T_{s}}
\]

\end_inset

where the integral is over 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-\frac{\pi}{T_{s}},\frac{\pi}{T_{s}}\right)$
\end_inset

 because integrating around the 0th sinc is the same as integrating around
 any other.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P\left(j\omega\right) & = & \frac{2\pi}{T_{s}}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}\delta\left(\omega-\frac{2\pi k}{T_{s}}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{2\pi}{T_{s}}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}\delta\left(\omega-k\omega_{s}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
X_{p}\left(j\omega\right) & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\left(X\left(j\omega\right)\star P\left(j\omega\right)\right)\\
 & \text{\Rightarrow} & \text{by \ref{eq:convimpshift}}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{T_{s}}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}X\left(j\left(\omega-k\omega_{s}\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{p}\left(j\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is just the original 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(j\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 replicated at every multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 and scaled by 
\begin_inset Formula $1/T_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that the distance between adjacent replications is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega_{s}-\omega_{M}\right)-\omega_{M}=\omega_{s}-2\omega_{M}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{M}$
\end_inset

 is the highest frequency in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(j\omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}-2\omega_{M}<0\iff\omega_{s}<2\omega_{M}$
\end_inset

 then the replications will overlap and using a bandpass filter will pick
 up extra power for the frequencies in the overlap region.
 This is called aliasing.
 If you want to avoid aliasing then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}>2\omega_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This is Shannon sampling theorem and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\omega_{M}$
\end_inset

 is the Nyquist rate, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{M}$
\end_inset

 is the Nyquiest, or folding, frequency.
\end_layout

