DFT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Recapitulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Discrete time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all discrete-time complex exponential signal that are periodic
 with period fundamental period 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{k}\left[n\right]=e^{jk\omega_{0}n}=e^{jk\left(\frac{2\pi}{N}\right)n}
\]

\end_inset

Note there are only 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 distinct signals in this set because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{k+N}\left[n\right]=e^{j\left(k+N\right)\omega_{0}n}=e^{j\left(k+N\right)\left(\frac{2\pi}{N}\right)n}=e^{jk\left(\frac{2\pi}{N}\right)n}e^{jN\left(\frac{2\pi}{N}\right)n}=\phi_{k}\left[n\right]e^{j2\pi n}=\phi_{k}\left[n\right]\times1
\]

\end_inset

and so in general 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{k+rN}\left[n\right]=\phi_{k}\left[n\right]
\]

\end_inset

So the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 index indexes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

family
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of exponentials represented and the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 index indexes the values that that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

family
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 takes on.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{N}\coloneqq e^{j2\pi/N}
\]

\end_inset

A 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-periodic discrete-time signal can be expanded in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

discrete-time complex exponential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 basis
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
x\left[n\right] & = & \sum_{n=\left\langle N\right\rangle }a_{k}\left(W_{N}\right)^{kn}\label{eq:synthdtfs}\\
a_{k} & \coloneqq & \frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=\left\langle N\right\rangle }x\left[n\right]\left(W_{N}\right)^{-kn}\label{eq:analdtfs}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Note also that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{k}\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 periodic in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 so are the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The sum index notation 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\left\langle N\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 means the sum should be carried out over any 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 sequential values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An aperiodic discrete-time signal be represented as a continuous sum (integral)
 of exponentials
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x\left[n\right] & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{2\pi}X\left(e^{j\omega}\right)e^{j\omega n}d\omega\\
X\left(e^{j\omega}\right) & = & \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left[n\right]e^{-j\omega n}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

There are analogues here to the discrete case.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(e^{j\omega}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 periodic just like 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 in eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:analdtfs"

\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 periodic.
 The integral over an interval of length 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 is analogous to the sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 sequential values for the synthesis equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:synthdtfs"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Continuous time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Periodic continuous-time signals can be decomposed into Fourier components.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 periodic signal.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{x}\left(t\right) & = & \sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}a_{k}e^{jk\omega_{0}t}=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}a_{k}e^{jk\left(\frac{2\pi}{T}\right)t}\label{eq:ctfssyn}\\
a_{k} & = & \frac{1}{T}\int_{T}\tilde{x}\left(t\right)e^{-jk\omega_{0}t}dt=\frac{1}{T}\int_{T}\tilde{x}\left(t\right)e^{-jk\left(\frac{2\pi}{T}\right)t}dt\label{eq:ctfsanal}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Aperiodic continuous-time signal can are also amenable to Fourier analysis
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x\left(t\right) & = & \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}X\left(j\omega\right)e^{j\omega t}d\omega\\
X\left(j\omega\right) & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The continuous-time Fourier transform can be employed on periodic signals
 as well.
 Suppose we wanted to compute the Fourier series coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 for a 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 periodic signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 be an finite duration (aperiodic) signal that agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 over one period, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $s\leq t\leq s+T$
\end_inset

, and is zero elsewhere.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(j\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 but since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is zero outside of 
\begin_inset Formula $s\leq t\leq s+T$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(j\omega\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt=\int_{s}^{s+T}x\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt
\]

\end_inset

and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)=x\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 on this interval
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(j\omega\right)=\int_{s}^{s+T}x\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt=\int_{s}^{s+T}\tilde{x}\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt
\]

\end_inset

Comparing with eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ctfsanal"

\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=\frac{1}{T}\int_{T}\tilde{x}\left(t\right)e^{-jk\left(\frac{2\pi}{T}\right)t}=\frac{1}{T}\left.\int_{s}^{s+T}\tilde{x}\left(t\right)e^{-j\omega t}dt\right|_{\omega=\frac{2\pi k}{T}}=\frac{1}{T}\left.X\left(j\omega\right)\right|_{\omega=\frac{2\pi k}{T}}
\]

\end_inset

So the Fourier series coefficients for a periodic signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 can be computed by sampling the Fourier transform of 
\series bold
one period
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Z-Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response of an LTI system to an input of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]=z^{n}$
\end_inset

 was described in the section on complex exponentials.
 In general 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(z\right)\coloneqq\mathcal{Z}\left\{ x\left[n\right]\right\} \coloneqq\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left[n\right]z^{-n}
\]

\end_inset

is called the 
\emph on
Z-transform 
\emph default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]$
\end_inset

.
 By the convolution property the response of a system is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y\left(z\right)=H\left(z\right)X\left(z\right)
\]

\end_inset

In this context 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 is called the transfer function of the system.
 What's the relationship of the 
\emph on
z-
\emph default
transform to the discrete time Fourier transform? Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z=re^{j\omega}$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
X\left(re^{j\omega}\right) & = & \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}x\left[n\right]\left(re^{j\omega}\right)^{-n}\\
 & = & \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\left(\frac{x\left[n\right]}{r^{n}}\right)e^{-jn\omega}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{Z}\left\{ x\left[n\right]\right\} =\mathcal{F}\left\{ x\left[n\right]r^{-n}\right\} \label{eq:fourierztr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Specifically is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.X\left(z\right)\right|_{z=e^{j\omega}}=X\left(e^{j\omega}\right)=\mathcal{F}\left\{ x\left[n\right]\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Region of Convergence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fourierztr"

\end_inset

 we see that for the 
\emph on
z
\emph default
-transform to converge the Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left[n\right]r^{-n}$
\end_inset

 must converge and so it will converge and diverge for different values
 of 
\emph on
z
\emph default

